So first I tried using trigonometry to find the length of $\overset\longrightarrow{AD}$. Using special triangles (30-60-90 and 45-45-90), we see that $\left|\: \overline{AD} \: \right| = 2\sqrt{2}$. To find the height of $\triangle ADG$, we can use the symmetry of the octagon. Drawing a line from the center of the octagon to point D, we form two 45-45-90 right triangles. Calling the length of one side of an equilateral triangle (formed by connecting the vertices of the octagon) s, we have that $AD = \sqrt{2}s.$ Therefore, the height of $\triangle ADG$ is $\sqrt{s^2+2^2} = \sqrt{3}$. However, since we are looking for the area of $\triangle ADG$, we can use the formula for the area of an equilateral triangle, which is $A = \frac{s^2\sqrt{3}}{4}$. <answer> $8\sqrt{3}$

